WEBVTT

00:00.326 --> 00:03.594
On this episode of "MythBusters"...

00:03.644 --> 00:05.311
we lock and load...

00:06.277 --> 00:07.431
...get lost...

00:07.433 --> 00:09.642
Behold the Hyneman
in his natural habitat.

00:09.644 --> 00:11.071
...and let loose.

00:11.073 --> 00:12.302
Whoa!

00:12.304 --> 00:14.036
First up, Adam and Jamie

00:14.038 --> 00:15.994
look into the age-old anomaly

00:15.996 --> 00:17.596
that while blindfolded...

00:17.598 --> 00:19.423
I feel like I'm doing pretty good.

00:19.425 --> 00:21.424
...it's supposedly impossible

00:21.426 --> 00:23.256
to travel in a straight line.

00:23.258 --> 00:25.618
You drove us into the middle of a field.

00:25.620 --> 00:27.553
- Then...
- Somebody order a car?

00:27.555 --> 00:31.582
Kari, Grant, and Tory
find out if a fender bender...

00:31.584 --> 00:33.350
- Whoo!
- Whoa!

00:33.352 --> 00:34.850
...could detonate a trunk full

00:34.852 --> 00:37.614
of special-effects explosives.

00:37.616 --> 00:39.378
This is our target car.

00:39.380 --> 00:42.710
Stand by for a rocket-propelled car crash.

00:42.712 --> 00:44.178
Oh, my God. What just happened?

00:44.180 --> 00:45.543
I don't know!

00:48.111 --> 00:51.343
Who are the MythBusters?

00:51.345 --> 00:52.211
Adam Savage...

00:53.580 --> 00:54.979
I am the master of this stunt!

00:54.981 --> 00:58.013
- ...and Jamie Hyneman.
- Bye-bye!

00:58.015 --> 01:02.281
Between them, more than 30 years
of special-effects experience.

01:02.283 --> 01:04.181
Together with Grant Imahara...

01:04.183 --> 01:05.013
Whoo!

01:05.016 --> 01:05.814
...Kari Byron...

01:05.816 --> 01:07.613
Hi, Grant!

01:07.615 --> 01:09.546
- ...and Tory Belleci.
- Hit it!

01:09.548 --> 01:12.812
They don't just tell the myths.

01:12.814 --> 01:14.745
They put them to the test.

01:15.747 --> 01:18.747
MythBusters 9x15 - Walk a Straight Line
Original air date October 12, 2011

01:18.813 --> 01:22.313
Sync and corrected by atrn97g
www.addic7ed.com

01:22.411 --> 01:24.744
Watch out, because Adam and Jamie

01:24.746 --> 01:29.378
are about to walk, swim,
and drive blindfolded.

01:29.380 --> 01:30.879
What's with the blindfold?

01:30.881 --> 01:32.713
Ah, well, you ever work on something,

01:32.715 --> 01:34.347
and it's not going
the way you want it to,

01:34.349 --> 01:36.715
and you feel like you're just
going around in circles?

01:36.717 --> 01:38.617
I know exactly what you mean.

01:38.619 --> 01:41.451
Excellent, because that is what
this story is all about.

01:41.453 --> 01:44.452
The myth is that a human when blindfolded

01:44.454 --> 01:47.586
- cannot travel in a straight line.
- Really?

01:47.588 --> 01:50.387
It turns out that not only can't
we walk in a straight line

01:50.389 --> 01:51.755
but that left to our own devices,

01:51.757 --> 01:54.288
we will actually walk in circles

01:54.290 --> 01:55.622
and that this might be one of the reasons

01:55.624 --> 01:57.689
we might get lost in the woods.

01:57.691 --> 01:59.090
I thought with all
your survival training,

01:59.092 --> 02:00.757
you'd love this story.

02:00.759 --> 02:02.991
Hello? Jamie?

02:02.993 --> 02:05.692
Oh, he's gone.

02:06.927 --> 02:09.526
It's a deceptively simple concept

02:09.529 --> 02:13.063
that has puzzled serious
scientists for 100 years.

02:13.065 --> 02:14.931
Supposedly, when blindfolded,

02:14.933 --> 02:17.466
it's impossible for humans to travel,

02:17.468 --> 02:20.301
whether on foot, in water, or by road,

02:20.303 --> 02:21.335
in a straight line.

02:21.337 --> 02:22.402
It's a challenge

02:22.404 --> 02:25.403
Adam and Jamie just can't resist.

02:25.405 --> 02:27.271
Come on. Come on back in here.

02:27.273 --> 02:29.239
Did you even hear a word that I said?

02:29.241 --> 02:31.840
Yeah. Humans can't move in a
straight line while blindfolded.

02:31.842 --> 02:32.841
That's the story.

02:32.843 --> 02:34.075
How do you want to test it?

02:34.077 --> 02:35.809
Well, when I think
about moving in a straight line,

02:35.811 --> 02:36.910
I think about walking.

02:36.912 --> 02:38.344
I think you might be right.

02:38.346 --> 02:39.678
- Is that where you want to begin?
- Yeah.

02:39.680 --> 02:41.312
All we need is a couple blindfolds

02:41.314 --> 02:42.746
and a big wide-open field.

02:42.748 --> 02:44.114
Let's do it.

02:44.116 --> 02:46.115
A big field you say?

02:46.117 --> 02:47.415
How about this one?

02:47.417 --> 02:49.516
Our testing here is pretty straightforward.

02:49.518 --> 02:51.751
We've got a field
in which we can walk 3,000 feet

02:51.753 --> 02:53.686
in any direction that we chose.

02:53.688 --> 02:55.320
We've got a blindfold...

02:55.322 --> 02:57.622
this one here is from
my personal collection...

02:57.624 --> 03:00.324
and headphones to remove
any other stimulus.

03:00.326 --> 03:02.192
And we're just gonna try
and walk in a straight line

03:02.194 --> 03:03.260
and see what happens.

03:03.262 --> 03:04.995
Sure, we'll see what happens,

03:04.997 --> 03:08.197
but Jamie likes to be more science-y.

03:08.199 --> 03:09.765
We've got three ways
of telling how good we are

03:09.767 --> 03:11.800
at walking in a straight line
while blindfolded.

03:11.802 --> 03:15.369
First is by using the global
positioning system, or GPS.

03:15.371 --> 03:17.471
This little thing
will be plotting a map for us

03:17.473 --> 03:19.406
that we can look at afterwards.

03:19.408 --> 03:22.175
Secondly, we've got
these lovely little orange flags

03:22.177 --> 03:23.242
that we can place.

03:23.244 --> 03:24.977
- Are you ready to go?
- What?

03:24.979 --> 03:26.178
Oh!

03:26.180 --> 03:29.180
Then lastly, we'll know
if we hit the target

03:29.182 --> 03:31.215
because we will have had to have walked

03:31.217 --> 03:33.451
in more or less a straight line
to get there.

03:33.453 --> 03:35.819
How do I think I'm gonna do?

03:35.821 --> 03:37.286
I don't think I'm gonna be able

03:37.288 --> 03:39.055
to maintain an incredibly straight line,

03:39.057 --> 03:40.555
but I don't think
I'm gonna be that far off.

03:40.557 --> 03:43.191
I think I may veer
to the left or to the right,

03:43.193 --> 03:45.259
but I think I'll end up
pretty close to my goal

03:45.261 --> 03:47.527
of that cluster of trees over there.

03:47.529 --> 03:48.695
Or is it there?

03:48.697 --> 03:52.931
Okay, in 3, 2, 1, go!

03:52.933 --> 03:54.665
All he has to do

03:54.667 --> 03:57.767
is walk in a straight line
with his eyes closed.

03:57.769 --> 03:59.202
How hard can it be?

03:59.204 --> 04:01.970
It is a very weird thing

04:01.972 --> 04:04.706
to be walking without
any visual or auditory stimulus.

04:04.708 --> 04:06.007
What's really weird

04:06.009 --> 04:09.577
is, apparently, how
surprisingly difficult it is.

04:09.579 --> 04:12.146
You're holding a picture
of it in your head,

04:12.148 --> 04:13.981
and in your mind's eye,

04:13.983 --> 04:16.483
you're walking a nice straight trajectory

04:16.486 --> 04:18.119
across that landscape.

04:18.120 --> 04:19.620
Tickling at the back of your mind,

04:19.623 --> 04:21.289
you're thinking something might be wrong,

04:21.291 --> 04:23.925
but try as you might, you feel
like you're walking straight.

04:23.927 --> 04:25.660
Whoa!

04:25.662 --> 04:26.961
Whoa!

04:28.898 --> 04:30.131
You started out pretty nice,

04:30.133 --> 04:32.233
but after about 300 feet or so,

04:32.235 --> 04:34.068
you started to turn to the left,

04:34.070 --> 04:35.837
and you just kept doing that

04:35.839 --> 04:38.273
until you ended up
right back at the fence.

04:38.275 --> 04:42.077
I swear I thought I was walking
a perfectly straight line.

04:42.079 --> 04:44.946
Nothing told me
that I was possibly walking

04:44.948 --> 04:47.616
in a 200-foot-diameter circle.

04:47.618 --> 04:50.084
I am totally amazed by that result.

04:50.086 --> 04:53.421
A result nailed by the GPS trail.

04:53.423 --> 04:55.089
The astonishing disparity

04:55.091 --> 04:58.525
between Adam's perception
and his actual route

04:58.527 --> 05:00.594
is there for all to see.

05:02.898 --> 05:04.732
That is hilarious.

05:04.734 --> 05:06.801
It's a result that begs several questions.

05:06.803 --> 05:10.605
The first of which is,
will Jamie do any better?

05:10.607 --> 05:12.807
Jamie is blind man walking

05:12.809 --> 05:16.846
in 3, 2, 1, go!

05:16.848 --> 05:19.348
With all the confidence and certainty

05:19.350 --> 05:20.850
you'd expect from the Hyneman,

05:20.852 --> 05:23.419
he strides off towards the target tree...

05:23.421 --> 05:28.090
before veering off course
like he's got a short right leg.

05:28.092 --> 05:31.493
And any doubt that subtle
topographical features

05:31.495 --> 05:33.529
were the reason Adam went left

05:33.531 --> 05:37.399
are dispelled as Jamie
leans so far to the right,

05:37.401 --> 05:40.869
he turns back on himself
in a corkscrew pattern.

05:40.871 --> 05:44.873
I ended up right back
at the road just like you did.

05:44.875 --> 05:47.042
Time to delve deeper.

05:47.044 --> 05:49.044
Now, the question we have is,

05:49.046 --> 05:50.712
is that leaning that we each had

05:50.714 --> 05:52.648
to one direction or the other consistent?

05:52.650 --> 05:54.883
Walking blind... test number two.

05:54.885 --> 05:56.719
Is it something
that could be corrected for?

05:56.721 --> 05:58.187
Well, that's what
we're just about to find out.

06:00.190 --> 06:02.625
He's doing a little better this time.

06:02.627 --> 06:04.961
Adam's start is certainly straighter,

06:04.963 --> 06:06.996
but it's not long before the test

06:06.998 --> 06:09.532
literally takes a turn for the worse.

06:09.534 --> 06:11.600
Test two, I didn't walk straight,

06:11.602 --> 06:12.902
and I didn't even walk straight

06:12.904 --> 06:14.503
in the same way I didn't walk
straight the first time.

06:14.505 --> 06:16.338
I went in a circle
in the other direction.

06:16.340 --> 06:19.775
Yeah, two things are clear
from Adam's second test.

06:19.777 --> 06:22.011
His route is far from straight,

06:22.013 --> 06:25.615
and there's no discernable
pattern to his meandering.

06:25.617 --> 06:26.950
- Bye.
- Bye.

06:26.952 --> 06:30.053
A theory compounded on Jamie's second test

06:30.055 --> 06:31.421
because once again,

06:31.423 --> 06:35.025
he immediately heads off
in the wrong direction.

06:35.027 --> 06:36.693
I'm lost.

06:36.695 --> 06:38.061
Trying to walk in a straight line

06:38.063 --> 06:39.362
while being blindfolded

06:39.364 --> 06:41.030
is an exercise in futility

06:41.032 --> 06:46.370
because without any cues
like vision or sounds and so on,

06:46.372 --> 06:49.306
you're relying on purely mechanical means

06:49.308 --> 06:51.275
of determining your direction.

06:51.277 --> 06:53.610
I feel like he's Don Quixote,

06:53.612 --> 06:55.145
and I'm following him around.

06:55.147 --> 06:57.815
But you're fluid.
You're not like a machine.

06:57.817 --> 07:00.218
You can kind of meander and wander,

07:00.220 --> 07:03.520
and, in fact, that's kind of
what these GPS paths

07:03.522 --> 07:04.621
are showing,

07:04.623 --> 07:07.324
is this looks like a meandering stream.

07:07.326 --> 07:09.693
And that meandering corkscrewing

07:09.695 --> 07:12.496
leads Jamie and Adam
straight to a firm conclusion.

07:12.498 --> 07:13.563
Stop.

07:13.565 --> 07:15.165
We came here to look at the myth

07:15.167 --> 07:18.401
that a person who is blindfolded
cannot walk in a straight line,

07:18.403 --> 07:20.370
and we have definitely proven that

07:20.372 --> 07:22.005
with the data we've gathered.

07:22.007 --> 07:25.008
But the myth specifically says travel

07:25.010 --> 07:26.410
and not just walk.

07:26.412 --> 07:29.513
So to complete the data set
and nail the science,

07:29.515 --> 07:33.383
Adam and Jamie will be hitting
the highways and waterways,

07:33.385 --> 07:37.655
attempting alternative forms
of blindfold locomotion.

07:37.657 --> 07:38.990
What's next?

07:38.992 --> 07:40.091
Swimming blindfolded.

07:40.093 --> 07:41.760
- Well, we can't do that here.
- No.

07:41.762 --> 07:43.761
- Let's go someplace else.
- All right.

